1
00:00:00,919 --> 00:00:06,340
Renko chart is probably the most under-rated
trading concept, ignored by most traders.

2
00:00:06,340 --> 00:00:10,970
Although no single tool is going to instantly
make you a great trader, Renko charts will

3
00:00:10,970 --> 00:00:14,930
allow you to see the market in a different
way, and will also help you stick to your

4
00:00:14,930 --> 00:00:16,000
trading plan better.

5
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:20,530
That’s why in today’s video we’ll discuss
about Renko charts and I will share how to

6
00:00:20,530 --> 00:00:24,910
adjust them correctly for scalping and day
trading.

7
00:00:24,910 --> 00:00:30,580
Renko charts are a new way to view the price
of an asset that filters out minor price movements.

8
00:00:30,580 --> 00:00:35,929
The chart looks like a series of bricks placed
at a 45-degree angle to each other.

9
00:00:35,929 --> 00:00:40,799
If you analyze these 2 two charts, you immediately
spot the striking differences between a regular

10
00:00:40,799 --> 00:00:43,000
candlestick chart and a Renko chart.

11
00:00:43,000 --> 00:00:47,889
You can see that those small fluctuations
on classic charts are removed, and price trends

12
00:00:47,889 --> 00:00:51,660
are easier to spot on the Renko chart.

13
00:00:51,660 --> 00:00:57,350
Renko charts are easier to read because the
markers on the chart—which are called bricks,

14
00:00:57,350 --> 00:01:01,359
boxes, or blocks—are more uniform compared
to candlestick charts.

15
00:01:01,359 --> 00:01:05,339
Traditional candlestick charts plot new bars
as time passes.

16
00:01:05,339 --> 00:01:09,359
For instance, a one-minute chart will plot
a new bar every minute.

17
00:01:09,359 --> 00:01:12,009
On the other hand, a Renko chart:
• Does not depend on time

18
00:01:12,009 --> 00:01:16,689
• Plots a new bar only when the market moves
beyond a certain amount

19
00:01:16,689 --> 00:01:21,200
Being independent of time is the defining
characteristic of a Renko chart.

20
00:01:21,200 --> 00:01:27,920
So, it depends only on price action, creating
a smoothed chart with less noise.

21
00:01:27,920 --> 00:01:31,350
Each brick on a Renko chart is a candlestick
with no shadows.

22
00:01:31,350 --> 00:01:35,460
You need only one key parameter for Renko
charts – the brick size.

23
00:01:35,460 --> 00:01:41,030
The brick size is the price range that the
market must cover before a new brick is plotted.

24
00:01:41,030 --> 00:01:45,319
You can set the brick size in pips, ticks,
or cents, depending on the market you’re

25
00:01:45,319 --> 00:01:46,319
trading.

26
00:01:46,319 --> 00:01:50,450
And, for a Renko chart to reverse, meaning
the brick to change its color, price action

27
00:01:50,450 --> 00:01:53,259
must reverse by at least two brick sizes.

28
00:01:53,259 --> 00:01:58,310
Let’s say you trade Forex, and we’ll pick
the EUR/JPY pair.

29
00:01:58,310 --> 00:02:03,359
It you want to set your brick size to 5 pips
for example, you just have to adjust the settings

30
00:02:03,359 --> 00:02:07,049
of the Renko box size to 0.05.

31
00:02:07,049 --> 00:02:10,190
If you want a ten pip box size, you set it
0.1.

32
00:02:10,190 --> 00:02:13,690
I use Tradingview, by the way, to trade with
Renko bars.

33
00:02:13,690 --> 00:02:23,319
For GBP/USD or EUR/USD, for a 10 pip brick
size you set the box size to 0.001.

34
00:02:23,319 --> 00:02:28,030
You can set the values of the box size depending
on your trading style: scalping, day trading

35
00:02:28,030 --> 00:02:33,780
or swing trading, and you can change the value
of the Renko chart to suit your trading needs.

36
00:02:33,780 --> 00:02:37,970
If you trade stocks, a box size of 1, is the
equivalent of 1 dollar.

37
00:02:37,970 --> 00:02:43,250
I find this value to be perfect for swing
trading and even day trading strategies.

38
00:02:43,250 --> 00:02:48,060
Every time the stock moves 1 dollar, a new
brick is formed.

39
00:02:48,060 --> 00:02:52,780
Since the brick size is the only parameter,
a successful Renko strategy is highly dependent

40
00:02:52,780 --> 00:02:53,780
on it.

41
00:02:53,780 --> 00:02:57,049
There are 2 methods used to set this parameter.

42
00:02:57,049 --> 00:02:59,040
Fixed Amount
Average True Range

43
00:02:59,040 --> 00:03:03,220
First, let’s talk about the FIXED AMOUNT
method.

44
00:03:03,220 --> 00:03:08,099
Using a set number of ticks/pips/cents as
the brick size is the simplest method.

45
00:03:08,099 --> 00:03:12,340
But unless you are already familiar with the
market, it’s challenging to arrive at a

46
00:03:12,340 --> 00:03:13,660
suitable figure.

47
00:03:13,660 --> 00:03:15,670
You need some trial and error here.

48
00:03:15,670 --> 00:03:20,200
If you want to see more bricks plotted, reduce
the size the box size.

49
00:03:20,200 --> 00:03:24,090
This approach is indicated if you prefer scalping
or day trading.

50
00:03:24,090 --> 00:03:29,730
If you enjoy swing trading, increase the box
size, and in this way less bricks will be

51
00:03:29,730 --> 00:03:30,780
plotted.

52
00:03:30,780 --> 00:03:34,409
Be careful not to use a brick size that’s
too small.

53
00:03:34,409 --> 00:03:38,610
If your brick size is too small, the Renko
chart will be volatile.

54
00:03:38,610 --> 00:03:42,900
As a result, it loses its intended effect
of smoothing price action.

55
00:03:42,900 --> 00:03:46,650
There is no rule that works for every currency
pair or stock.

56
00:03:46,650 --> 00:03:51,049
When I use Renko, I just eyeball the chart,
and try a few different box sizes.

57
00:03:51,049 --> 00:03:54,269
If it is too choppy I try increasing the box
size.

58
00:03:54,269 --> 00:03:59,280
Then I try decreasing it, because maybe there
are trends to be captured within the choppy

59
00:03:59,280 --> 00:04:00,490
trading.

60
00:04:00,490 --> 00:04:04,310
Smaller boxes mean more trend changes and
more trades.

61
00:04:04,310 --> 00:04:09,489
Big boxes mean fewer trend changes and fewer
trades.

62
00:04:09,489 --> 00:04:13,189
Second approach involves the AVERAGE TRUE
RANGE (ATR) for brick sizes

63
00:04:13,189 --> 00:04:17,910
The advantage of this method is that it factors
in changes in price volatility.

64
00:04:17,910 --> 00:04:20,350
A typical value is the 14-period ATR.

65
00:04:20,350 --> 00:04:24,940
So the brick size is based on the ATR value
at the time the chart is created.

66
00:04:24,940 --> 00:04:30,220
Should the ATR value change the next day,
then this new ATR value will be used to set

67
00:04:30,220 --> 00:04:32,000
the brick size.

68
00:04:32,000 --> 00:04:33,040
Which one is better?

69
00:04:33,040 --> 00:04:38,380
I prefer the fixed value because the ATR value
might change and can cause the Renko chart

70
00:04:38,380 --> 00:04:41,200
to change significantly whenever it is updated.

71
00:04:41,200 --> 00:04:47,830
That’s just my preference, but I know a
few traders that use the ATR Brick size successfully.

72
00:04:47,830 --> 00:04:52,430
One characteristic of Renko charts that should
be understood is that the charts don’t show

73
00:04:52,430 --> 00:04:54,050
all price points.

74
00:04:54,050 --> 00:04:59,300
Consider that you are using a Renko brick
of 3 pips and price moves 5 pips in the opposite

75
00:04:59,300 --> 00:05:00,300
direction.

76
00:05:00,300 --> 00:05:04,920
Since that is not enough price movement to
make another Renko brick, there will be 2

77
00:05:04,920 --> 00:05:07,890
pips of price that does not show on the Renko
chart.

78
00:05:07,890 --> 00:05:12,740
When I first started day trading Renko day
charts, this bothered me a lot, especially

79
00:05:12,740 --> 00:05:16,950
after trading with time and classic candlesticks
for so many years.

80
00:05:16,950 --> 00:05:21,470
There are indicators that add ‘wicks’
to the Renko bricks to show these prices,

81
00:05:21,470 --> 00:05:24,710
but these start to add some of the ‘noise’
back to the chart.

82
00:05:24,710 --> 00:05:30,370
It’s up to you if you want to add or remove
the wicks on Renko bars.

83
00:05:30,370 --> 00:05:35,230
So the most important step in creating a successful
Renko strategy is setting the size of the

84
00:05:35,230 --> 00:05:36,230
brick.

85
00:05:36,230 --> 00:05:39,470
It may be $0.10 in the stock market or 10
pips in forex market.

86
00:05:39,470 --> 00:05:44,620
What you must remember is that a brick forms
on the Renko chart once the price has moved

87
00:05:44,620 --> 00:05:46,160
that amount, and not before.

88
00:05:46,160 --> 00:05:51,760
A candlestick chart, on the other hand, shows
the price movement over a period of time,

89
00:05:51,760 --> 00:05:54,260
such as one minute or one day.

90
00:05:54,260 --> 00:05:59,160
While there is a time axis along the bottom
of a Renko chart, there is no set time limit

91
00:05:59,160 --> 00:06:02,220
for how long a Renko box takes to form.

92
00:06:02,220 --> 00:06:05,560
It could take 4 minutes, three hours, or eight
days.

93
00:06:05,560 --> 00:06:10,860
It all depends on how volatile the pricing
of the asset is and what brick size you set.

94
00:06:10,860 --> 00:06:15,450
So Renko charts ignore the time aspect and
only focus on price changes.

95
00:06:15,450 --> 00:06:21,180
If the brick value is set at 10 points, a
move of 10 points or more is required to draw

96
00:06:21,180 --> 00:06:22,350
another brick.

97
00:06:22,350 --> 00:06:26,720
Price movements less than 10 points would
be ignored and the Renko chart would remain

98
00:06:26,720 --> 00:06:29,220
unchanged.

99
00:06:29,220 --> 00:06:34,380
Renko charts are most useful to day traders
and scalpers for spotting trends, areas of

100
00:06:34,380 --> 00:06:38,210
support and resistance, breakouts, and reversals.

101
00:06:38,210 --> 00:06:42,710
The chart's simplicity can make it easier
to see those price actions and signals for

102
00:06:42,710 --> 00:06:44,130
making trades.

103
00:06:44,130 --> 00:06:50,500
This is because Renko charts filter the noise
by focusing exclusively on minimum price changes.

104
00:06:50,500 --> 00:06:54,290
Renko bricks are not added unless price changes
by a specific amount.

105
00:06:54,290 --> 00:06:59,840
Thus, it’s easy to spot important highs
and lows, and identify key support and resistance

106
00:06:59,840 --> 00:07:00,960
levels.

107
00:07:00,960 --> 00:07:06,030
Armed with this information, you can identify
uptrends by analyzing higher highs and higher

108
00:07:06,030 --> 00:07:10,690
lows or downtrends with lower lows and lower
highs.

109
00:07:10,690 --> 00:07:15,690
The stronger the trend, the more renko blocks
will be plotted.

110
00:07:15,690 --> 00:07:19,840
Renko charts are particularly good at finding
support and resistance areas because they

111
00:07:19,840 --> 00:07:22,960
condense long, but static periods.

112
00:07:22,960 --> 00:07:27,680
This makes it easier to see where price support
and price resistance is occurring.

113
00:07:27,680 --> 00:07:31,840
Renko Charts are very visual to display obvious
support and resistance levels.

114
00:07:31,840 --> 00:07:36,060
With classic candlestick charts, there is
a lot of subjectivity and extra work that

115
00:07:36,060 --> 00:07:40,130
goes into identifying good and precise areas
of support and resistance.

116
00:07:40,130 --> 00:07:45,900
In this example, notice how simple it is to
plot the support and resistance levels.

117
00:07:45,900 --> 00:07:51,140
And most interestingly, notice how price reacts
to these support/resistance levels to the

118
00:07:51,140 --> 00:07:53,280
right side of the chart.

119
00:07:53,280 --> 00:07:58,490
Even if you prefer to use candlesticks, using
Renko as your tool to find these price levels

120
00:07:58,490 --> 00:08:02,220
will help you a lot to find the best areas
to trade from.

121
00:08:02,220 --> 00:08:08,310
Also as with support and resistance identification,
chart patterns are also much easier to recognize

122
00:08:08,310 --> 00:08:10,240
on a Renko chart.

123
00:08:10,240 --> 00:08:13,510
This Renko chart shows several classical chart
patterns.

124
00:08:13,510 --> 00:08:19,920
I can spot an inverted head and shoulders,
a double top, flag patterns, traingles and

125
00:08:19,920 --> 00:08:22,300
so on.

126
00:08:22,300 --> 00:08:26,440
With the bricks on a Renko chart, you can
spot price clusters quickly.

127
00:08:26,440 --> 00:08:29,530
These clusters are great demand and supply
zones.

128
00:08:29,530 --> 00:08:36,430
A simple guideline is to look for boxes formed
by alternating bricks within a price range.

129
00:08:36,430 --> 00:08:42,209
This example shows how a Renko chart highlighted
an effective supply zone.You can notice several

130
00:08:42,209 --> 00:08:48,550
renko Bricks within the same price range,
which projected a supply zone, which was respected

131
00:08:48,550 --> 00:08:51,310
by the market later on.

132
00:08:51,310 --> 00:08:57,019
Renko charts can also be helpful with uncovering
trends and patterns that are obscured in time-based

133
00:08:57,019 --> 00:09:01,029
charts and for simplifying complicated chart
structures.

134
00:09:01,029 --> 00:09:05,569
When the price is trending, Renko charts provide
a simple way to stick with the trend.

135
00:09:05,569 --> 00:09:10,970
Don't exit until there is a reversal—a confirmed
box of the opposite color.

136
00:09:10,970 --> 00:09:15,430
You can use typical technical analysis to
help identify potential turning points or

137
00:09:15,430 --> 00:09:20,620
the start of a trend, and then use Renko charts
to stick with that trend, or you could simply

138
00:09:20,620 --> 00:09:22,449
trade based on Renko.

139
00:09:22,449 --> 00:09:27,649
A new box color equals a potential trend change,
but this doesn’t mean a new position must

140
00:09:27,649 --> 00:09:29,800
be initiated right away.

141
00:09:29,800 --> 00:09:34,040
This method can result in lots of losing trades
when the price is choppy.

142
00:09:34,040 --> 00:09:38,970
Use Renko charts as an additional tool, in
conjunction with support and resistance levels.

143
00:09:38,970 --> 00:09:45,490
I encourage you to use Renko only on certain
forex pairs and stocks that trend well.

144
00:09:45,490 --> 00:09:50,620
Find a box size that allows you to capture
the bulk of the price moves, but also minimizes

145
00:09:50,620 --> 00:09:52,680
the consolidation periods.

146
00:09:52,680 --> 00:09:57,930
Unfortunately, the consolidation periods can't
be avoided...if the price is oscillating back

147
00:09:57,930 --> 00:10:00,170
and forth, so will Renko charts.

148
00:10:00,170 --> 00:10:04,990
For this reason, I prefer to add a moving
average to Renko charts, to keep me on the

149
00:10:04,990 --> 00:10:06,930
right side of the trend.

150
00:10:06,930 --> 00:10:11,990
Very important: the moving averages will be
computed using the Renko bricks, not the actual

151
00:10:11,990 --> 00:10:12,990
bars.

152
00:10:12,990 --> 00:10:17,800
Therefore I advise you to use shorter period
averages because the Renko technique is filtering

153
00:10:17,800 --> 00:10:21,269
out most of the market noise already.

154
00:10:21,269 --> 00:10:23,481
Renko charts are not perfect and have their
limitations.

155
00:10:23,481 --> 00:10:29,600
A few drawbacks have already been addressed:
First, Renko charts are not so helpful in

156
00:10:29,600 --> 00:10:31,170
choppy periods.

157
00:10:31,170 --> 00:10:36,480
Also, the simplification of Renko charts comes
at a cost, because some price information

158
00:10:36,480 --> 00:10:37,480
is lost.

159
00:10:37,480 --> 00:10:44,889
A third limitation is related to fact that
price has to move quite a bit to cause a reversal.

160
